Egypt puts first freely elected president in office
Muhammad Morsi has been sworn in as an inaugural, but his triumphant day will hardly end egypt's political unrest.
ISLAMIST Mohamed Morsi promised a "new Egypt" when he was inaugurated as the country's first freely elected president, after Hosni Mubark, who was deposed 16 months earlier.
In his inauguration before the Supreme Constitutional Court, Morsi also became the first freely elected Islamic president in the Arab world and egypt's fifth head of state since the overthrow of the monarchy some 60 years ago.
He was sworn in in front of 18 judges dressed in black goons in a mansion built overlooking the Nile, which resembles an ancient Egyptian temple.
"We are striving for a better tomorrow, a new Egypt and a second republic," Morsi said at a ceremony broadcast live on state television.
"The Egyptian people today laid the foundation for a new life – absolute freedom, true democracy, and stability," said Morsi, a 60-year-old U.S.-trained engineer and member of the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group that has been the target of scathing attacks by individual governments for most of the 84 years since its inception as an illegal organization.
Hundreds of soldiers and police officers guarded the building when Morsi arrived in a small motor car motorloute shortly after 11 a.m. local time.
Only a few hundred supporters gathered outside the courthouse to celebrate the president, and unlike the presidential pomp of Mubarak's term, traffic was only briefly halted so that the motorcade could pass through the usually busy road connecting the city center with the suburbs to the south.
The personal prestige of Morsi, derisively referred to as the Muslim Brotherhood's uncharistic "reserve tire," has soared since his victory and his speech on Friday, which aimed to present him not only as a candidate for Islamists, but also for all those who want to end the rebellion against the authoritarian Mubark.
"Egypt is now a civil, national, constitutional and modern state," Morsi, dressed in a blue formal suit with a red tie, told judges in the wood-paneled chamber where he was sworn in.
Morsi later traveled to Cairo University to deliver his inaugural address.
While he stood at attention, he received an official welcome from a military band that played the national anthem.
Military Commander Field Marshal Hussein Tantanya was present.
His arrival was accompanied by chants of "army and people are one hand" from the mouths of hundreds of people gathered in the university's main lecture hall.
The University of Cairo was founded in 1908 as a center of secular education and later became a bastion of Islamic student movements in the 1970s.
Morsi took a symbolic oath on Friday in Tahrir Square, the birth of the revolution that ended Mubarak's authoritarian rule last year, and solemnly vowed to reassert the presidential powers taken from his office by the military council that took them from the ousted leader.
But by agreeing to take an official oath in court, rather than before parliament, as is customary, he acquiesced to the will of the military, suggesting that the power struggle would continue.
Morsi's speech in Tahrir Square was full of dramatic populist gestures.
