Is europe's elite ready for trade with Britain?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with the promise of combining businesses and defining what changes british entrepreneurs and job-creating companies want to see in their relationship with the EU.
To this end, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey, in which we asked leading British entrepreneurs about their views on Britain, trade and the EU.
YouGov interviewed 1,000 business leaders representing British businesses of all sizes and from different sectors and regions.
The results of the survey will come as a surprise to many.
We found that the vast majority of businesses are now trying to export outside Europe, focusing on countries that are modernising and growing while EU countries stagnate.
They want to see the government prioritize new trade ties with countries like China, India, and Brazil rather than get bogged down in the long and erring process of reforming europe's mysterious institutions.
When asked about their views on specific policy areas – from monopoly regulations to product laws – most entrepreneurs expressed the view that control of these key competences should be returned to Westminster.
There was widespread dissatisfaction with the single market, and entrepreneurs said that the cost of Brussels regulations now outweighed the benefits of being part of Europe's business – even 40 percent of large enterprises, traditionally the most pro-European, agreed.
Finally, our survey of business leaders revealed the most ediceous recognition, namely that a clear majority wants Britain to seek to change the treaty and relationship with the EU, which should be based on trade, not politics.
The findings, identified by businesses of different sizes and core business groups, show that the business sector is pushing for a "meaningful change" that will bring influence back to Britain.
The stakes are high – achieving treaty change and a better deal for Britain can mean 16% of the vote in a referendum to remain in the EU.
The Prime Minister should not hesitate: this survey shows that British trade supports his plan to amend the terms of Britain's EU membership.
It also shows that the business sector expects this amendment to mark a significant shift from the current balance of power back towards Britain.
A better deal for Britain is possible, and increasingly necessary as the eurozone embarks on a path to closer economic and fiscal union.
Jobs and growth in Britain must be a priority, and as the results of our survey show, for business this means a refocusing on trade and a fundamental change in Brussels' regulatory approach.
