The UK government has announced a study aimed at increasing the benefits of the HS2 rail project for Scotland.
HS2's work suggests that high-speed services for Scotland and northern England will begin when the first phase is launched in 2026.
Transport Minister Baroness Kramer said the project would "bring the UK together."
Scottish Transport Secretary Keith Brown said he was "thrilled" to be working with the UK government on the plan.
The first phase will consist of a new high-speed train line between London and the West Midlands.
After Phase Two is completed, the line will run from Manchester to Leeds.
In June, the government revised the estimated cost of building a high-speed line between London and northern England from GBP 32.7 billion to GBP 42.6 billion.
The UK government, which has held talks with transport scotland's national transport authority, has commissioned HS2 to look at additional rail capacity and the possibility of improving travel times for northern England and Scotland.
This includes the possibility of possible travel times from Glasgow and Edinburgh to London corresponding to three hours or less.
Baroness Kramer said: "Our goal for HS2 is really a national network that better connects the UK and its cities."
We gave SH2 the green light because the benefit it will bring is enormous.
Without this, we are facing a crisis in the capacity of our rail network.
But it is also about connectivity – 18 cities, including Glasgow and Edinburgh, will be better connected across the UK thanks to HS2.
Scottish Secretary Alistair Carmichael added: "Today's announcement is good news for Scotland."
On the Scottish Government, Keith Brown called on Mr Carmichael to "unequivocally" support Scottish integration into the HS2 network.
Mr Brown said: "The high-speed line has the potential to deliver immeasurable economic benefits to Scotland, but it also adds economic weight to Scotland's overall high-speed rail case across the UK."
So we are working with the UK Government to explore the possibilities of bringing high-speed rail to Scotland to bring benefits to everyone and to complement the Glasgow-Edinburgh line, which the Scottish Government plans to do anyway.
I look forward to reviewing the report on this study with British ministers over the next year and to making joint decisions on the next steps.
Frontier Airlines is going to charge for hand luggage
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 for carrying hand luggage on board on its flights.
Frontier Airlines plans to introduce a charge of up to $100 for hand luggage and $2 for coffee or soda, although in its announcement On Wednesday they said passengers would be able to keep the entire can.
The new hand luggage charge applies to luggage in the upper storage compartment, so small luggage under the seat will continue to be free.
Frontier says it will charge $25 if the fee is paid in advance and $100 if passengers wait until they arrive at the gate.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O'Malley said the $100 fee is intended to encourage passengers to take care of payment in advance.
"We don't want to collect this fee," she said.
Airlines started charging for the first and second bags in 2008.
Passengers tried to avoid these charges and stuffed as much space as they could into hand luggage in the storage compartment, so there was often no space in that space.
Fees are one way to teach passengers to take fewer things on board.
O'Malley said the purpose of this new fee really isn't to raise more money.
The point is that Frontier's most loyal customers have made it very clear that finding a place in the upper storage space is becoming increasingly difficult.
Passengers who purchase tickets on the company's website will not pay.
This means that one passenger queuing at frontier gate can bring luggage for which they pay nothing, while the other passenger in the queue pays $100 for the same luggage.
O'Malley said the check-in website and procedures will be adjusted to ensure passengers learn about the charge before arriving at the gate.
Frontier's new hand luggage fee will not be in effect until the summer, but no date has yet been set.
Passengers often complain about baggage fees and other charges, but airlines love them.
They argue that baggage handling costs money, and passengers who request the service should pay for it.
Many on Wall Street see the additional baggage charge as a sign that airlines are trying to raise enough money to cover the cost of air travel after years of losses.
However, most did not touch the hand luggage charges.
Spirit Airlines was the first to charge for hand luggage three years ago, and another low-cost airline, Allegiant Air, later followed suit.
The only company that also has such fees is Hungary's Wizz Air, says aviation consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors additional charges.
In his December 2011 report, he estimated that Spirit's hand luggage fee would bring in $50 million a year.
Sorensen, a former Midwest Airlines executive, recently flew with Spirit and wondered what he saw at the gate when passengers encountered Spirit's unusual hand luggage fee.
"Getting on a plane was the smoothest thing I've ever seen in my aviation career," he said.
I expected to see teeth grinding and fighting at the gate.
The plane was full, he said, "and boarding took place in no time."
Frontier will also apply fees for coffee, tea, soda and juice, following Spirit's example.
Frontier said passengers who receive lemonade or juice can keep the entire can and the coffee will be refilled free of charge.
Water will continue to be served free of charge.
US Airways briefly tried to introduce beverage charges in 2008, but backed away seven months later after complaints from passengers, and no other major airline imitated it.
Frontier's latest move to charge for hand luggage if passengers do not purchase a flight directly from the airline is its latest effort to direct customers directly to its website.
Airlines pay online travel agents like Orbitz from $10 to $25 for each ticket sold.
This has given all airlines an incentive to lead passengers to make purchases directly from them, instead of doing so through online travel agencies.
However, Frontier has gone the furthest in this area.
In September, it began giving customers who purchased through an online travel agency only half the miles as part of a loyalty program.
On Wednesday, she cut the reward for miles flown to 25 percent of the miles from the trip.
So a 1,000-mile journey with Frontier purchased through an internet travel agency means a reward of 250 miles.
The company also allows customers to choose their seat in advance only if they make a purchase directly through frontier's website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base in its hometown of Denver, but its business is starting to shrink and losing money.
Revenue fell 9 percent and transportation capacity shrank nearly 13 percent in the first quarter, according to financial results released Wednesday by business partner Republic Airways Holdings.
Republic is also trying to solve Frontier's financial problems by selling this airline.
