In November last year, an analysis picked up over 11,000 job advertisements, 4,300 of which were published in the daily press and 6,800 ads (62 percent) online.
The Internet is therefore becoming the most important medium for publishing job offers.
As of 2005, when the survey was first conducted, its share was 26 percent.
In the last two surveys (2007, 2010), it stabilised at around 60 percent.
According to the analysis, the advertising of job opportunities largely reflects the current situation on the labour market.
An example is simply comparing the number of advertisements published during periods of economic prosperity and in times of economic crisis.
For example, in 2007, almost 25 900 advertisements were published in the same reference period, less than half in 2012.
The offer of jobs on the Internet is oriented towards a narrower, especially more qualified group of professions.
On the other hand, the offer of employment in the daily press covers a wider range of professions, including blue-collar ones, said pavlína Šťastnová, the author of the analysis.
The level of representation of selected professional groups varies between media.
Advertisements seeking managers and executives, sales representatives, programmers and financial experts have taken the top positions on the Internet.
The position of programmers or small business leaders was only on the Internet.
In the daily press, the share of these professional professions is significantly lower, on the contrary, a large representation belongs mainly to service and working-class professions.
Of course, education is one of the most frequently mentioned requirements expressed by employers through advertising.
Other areas of reference included knowledge of foreign languages, especially English.
In the daily press, the requirement to know a foreign language was reported in three percent of advertisements, and on the Internet in 37 percent.
