Similarly, pedetes made of rocks from the area form an interesting geological exposice.
Each stop also shows the name of the sponsor.
Coal Hill is the remnant of a young volcano.
Although the data from radiometric measurements of age vary somewhat, the last eruption here was about 1.5 million years ago.
It is therefore younger than The Great Roudný (age 3.3 million years) and older than Venus's volcano (age 0.8 million years).
The volcano was born by an explosion.
In it, it cast out a considerable amount of volcanic ash, along with fragments of rock from the subsoil, which by burning it acquired a reddish-brown color.
At the end of this phase, lava flowed to the surface - today it is a layer of porous bumble state up to 13 meters powerful.
The second eruption effahed red, brownish-red, and in places black tuffs.
Their layer is powerful up to 50 meters, and part of it is accessible in the wall of the quarry.
In the tuffs, volcanic bombs are up to 1 meter in size, and the second eruption was ended by an outpouring of lava.
At the end of the activity, lava flowed out of the volcano, which today forms up to 50 m thick layer of slag-like bumble state.
Volcanoes where volcanic ash effluent alternates with lava flows are the most common type of volcanoes.
Because they're actually composed of layers, they've been named stratovolcanas.
The original volcanic cone was gradually subjected to erosion.
However, it was endangered only by the mining of rocks in the quarry on the south side.
The most intensive mining took place here from 1953 to 1962.
Tufu were added to the concrete, which was then lighter and had better thermal insulation properties.
Mining was stopped under pressure from experts and the public, thus preserving this unique place.
