Scientists shed more light on how tail movements are related to the dog's mood
Previous research has shown that joyful dogs wagging their tails more to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nervous dogs wave their tails mostly to the left.
Now, however, scientists say that other dogs can notice and react to these subtle differences in tail movement.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neurobiologist at the University of Trento, said: "It is well known in humans that the left and right side of the brain have different links to stimuli that arouse positive or negative emotions."
We tried to observe the same thing in other species.
He added that, as is the case with humans, the right side of the brain is responsible for left-handed movements and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres play a different role in emotions.
In an effort to learn more about how dogs respond to the asymmetrical wagging of other dogs' tails, researchers monitored animals that watched movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of these animals and analyzed their behavior.
It probably won't be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side, and sometimes to the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: "We showed dogs films about dogs – whether in the natural version or in the form of a silhouette – to get rid of any confusing stimuli, and we were also able to adjust the movement of the tail and depict it more to the right or left."
When the animals saw an otherwise bland dog move its tail to the right (from the point of view of a dog wagging its tail), it remained completely calm.
But when she recorded the tail filming mostly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog wagging its tail), their heart rate increased and the animals looked insecure.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think dogs would knowingly communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he believes that dogs have learned from experience which movements they need to look out for and which they do not have to look out for.
He said: "If you encounter dogs several times and the movement of their tail in one direction is repeatedly associated with rather friendly behavior, and movement to the right breeds less friendly behavior, you will react based on this experience."
Researchers say the findings can help dog owners, veterinarians and trainers better understand their animals' emotions.
Dog behaviour expert John Bradshaw, a university professor of animal science at the University of Bristol, said it was not the first study to examine whether the left and right side were important to dogs.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University found that dogs turn their heads to the left when they observe an aggressive dog, and on the right when they look at a cheerful dog.
And in another expert paper from the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: "Dogs were more likely to get to know a dog robot when it cocked its tail to the left rather than to the right, when they were becoming insecure – just the opposite of the Italian study."
The difference, he says, can be made by the fact that dogs in these different studios did not fully think of animals in movies or dog robots as dogs.
He explained that a study on how dogs respond to real dogs could help.
"Although there is strong evidence in many different mammals that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be clarified – and dogs are no exception," he said.
But given how easy it is to record their behavior, it probably won't be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side and sometimes to the other.
