He described what the controversy was about and who was on whose side, he described in an exclusive interview with the Daily Mail.
How do you feel about the outcome of the election?
ČSSD certainly expected a much better result.
Has it been damaged in our country by the fact that there were disputes within the party in the media before the election?
I imagine that social democracy could have a better electoral outcome.
But on the other hand, it corresponds to the state in which ČSSD is now.
It's a party that has its own internal problems, it's internally ill, and people perceive that everything is not right in it.
They made that clear in the election.
What are the internal diseases of the ČSSD?
I think the ODS has been going through a decline for some time now, and unfortunately, such things are now taking place in a social democracy.
It is that lobbyists, influential people who previously expected to find their prebends with the ODS, have moved to the people in the ČSSD and have influence over them.
This has to do with the fact that the police go around the offices of the Ostrava Municipality and collect computers.
It shows that ČSSD is not only composed of people who want the good of everyone else, but many of them think above all about their own good.
ČSSD is divided into two irreconcilable camps also in Prague, as can be seen in the current power struggle between Hašek and Sobotka.
But even that has been in the works for a long time.
What happened before the elections in Ostrava was just a harbinger of what is happening now in Prague.
Hasek's wing gradually occupied positions so that after the elections it could create a situation that would weaken Sobotka's wing.
One is in a situation in politics where sometimes you have to compromise.
But everyone has an internal boundary where you can't compromise anymore, and that's my case.
Originally, I did not want to run for the House, but when I perceived the whole thing within the party, I agreed with Luboš Zaorálek that I would try to get on the regional list in order to strengthen Sobotka's wing as mayor of Ostrava.
But Hask's wing gave it a clue.
Why are you on bohuslav sobotka's side and not Michal Hašek?
Slavek Sobotka is, in my opinion, a person who always talks primarily about the ČSSD program and, to some extent, visions for the party and for this country.
I'll admit, I haven't heard anything like that from the other side.
Michal Hašek is just fighting for power.
I do not understand how the Bureau, which is a lower body than the Central Executive Committee, can start simply dismissing the party chairman.
This is a power struggle regardless of everything and against the party's statutes.
In my opinion, what Michal Hašek has now demonstrated in Prague has ended his political career.
How did you perceive that the Ostrava leadership of the ČSSD did not approve you as a candidate.
Political parties are based on a competition to see who will be placed.
The competition should be largely based on the program visions and the ability of those people to fulfill those visions.
Of course, there are also people who do not have much ability or vision in this competition, but a political party is an elevator to money that they would not get elsewhere.
The problem is when these people start to come to the fore by breaking the rules without scruples, they violate the party's statutes.
They use their practices to make political parties mafias and, in my opinion, they also violate the laws of the Czech Republic.
Drawing attention to this problem is more important to me than taking into account whether any Kajnar has a political future.
It is important that the parties start respecting the statutes.
Is that why you filed an application to the court before the elections for interim measures against the form of the ČSSD candidate in the Moravian-Silesian Region?
The current CSSD District Executive Committee in Ostrava consolidates its power by being able to abolish organizations that do not suit it, purposefully founding new organizations, gradually firing uncomfortable party members.
An example is that they wanted to expel Richard Bednařík from the club of representatives, but he filed a lawsuit against it, and they then overturned the resolution to expel him.
This shows that, while it is the last resort to enforce the party's statutes through the courts, it is the only option when the other methods and supervisory authorities within the ČSSD have ceased to function.
The aim of the leadership of the Ostrava ČSSD, headed by Deputy Adam Rykala, is to remove you from the position of mayor.
It is an open secret that the mayor of Poruba, Lumír Palyza, has a crush on this post.
That's right, Adam Rykala and Lumir Palyza are trying to do everything they can to get me recalled.
They promise people positions, they get votes, and for those votes, they consolidate their power in the party.
Going back to the past, everything that happened around baník ostrava football club and the purchase of the Bazala Stadium was just an excuse for them to attack me.
It was artificially staged so they could call me a man who puts money where it doesn't belong.
In doing so, the city bought property that is strategically of great value to it.
So how do you see it with your stay as mayor?
On Monday, the District Committee invited me and other people to consider staying in the ČSSD.
But I think it's like a thief yelling, "Catch the thief!"
If we look at the results of my work over the last eleven years, I do not see anyone in Ostrava's social democracy initiating and asserting, sometimes against party members, the emergence of so many development things, such as industrial zones or the expansion of a science and technology park.
Yet everything becomes uncomfortable.
I don't read it any other way than I'm getting in the way of others getting into the places they want.
Will you still be fighting these efforts?
Because if this republic is going to work well, so must political parties.
I can hardly believe that any party will be able to effectively run the state if it can't even control itself.
So I am not considering leaving čssd now, because I think that the person who is causing this party's cancer is not me, but these people who are trying to exte me.
