John Kerry admitted: Spying has gone too far!
The United States has sometimes gone "too far" in spying, US Diplomatic Chief John Kerry admitted during a video conference between Washington and London, according to AFP.
But, according to the minister, the collection of information served to avert terrorist attacks.
According to AFP, the "first admission from Washington" came amid fierce controversy on both sides of the Atlantic over scandalous revelations about mass data surveillance by the US National Security Agency (NSA), which has also been targeted by US allies.
"In some cases, I admit, as President (Barack Obama) did, some of these actions have gone too far, and we are making sure that this does not happen in the future," Kerry said.
In the interview, however, he defended his practice to date.
Collecting information, he said, is essential to combat terrorism and prevent assassinations such as the 9/11 attacks in the US, the Madrid bombings in March 2004, and the London attacks of July 2005.
"We prevented planes from falling, buildings exploding, and people being killed because we were able to be informed of the plots in a timely manner," Kerry stressed.
However, he again admitted that the collection of information 'in some cases has gone unreasonably far'.
The U.S. intelligence affair, which allegedly tracked hundreds of millions of phone calls, erupted in Europe this month.
Among other things, it turned out that the Americans were also tracking German Chancellor Angela Merkel's cell phone.
European leaders have made no hiding their indignation, and some have called on the European Union to try to reach an agreement with the United States that would conceal or significantly limit surveillance.
The royal commission heard that two employees of the Christian Youth Association (YMCA) had been charged before the prosecutions against Jonathan Lord.
The Royal Commission into Child Sexual Abuse has learned that two staff members of the Christian Young Men's Association (YMCA) in New South Wales were accused of sexually abusing children before charges were brought against child educator Jonathan Lord of Caringbah in 2011.
But the committee said in its opening statement to the commission that the association had never dealt with a case of child sexual abuse in their organization.
Ceo Phillip Hare was asked about a case in which one YMCA employee was charged with child pornography offences, and another where a YMCA gym teacher in Caringbah was convicted in 1991 of sexually harassing children in his care.
Mr. Hare told Gaili Furness, the commission's counsel, that he knew about the first case, but not the second.
He acknowledged that the YMCA's opening statement was also inaccurate, ncing on the fact that external audits had been carried out at the YMCA, which praised the organisation as a leading advocate for children's rights.
The evidence presented by the commission suggests that the YMCA was alerted to receiving the second lowest of the four possible assessments in an Audit by the Ministry of Education and Society in August this year.
Mr Hare, who started working with the YMCA when he was 21, admitted that management had failed to take Mr Lord down from him without making sure staff were aware of the obligation to report breaches of child safety rules.
Earlier this year, Lord was convicted of sexually harassing 12 boys during his two years at the YMCA.
He was jailed for a minimum of six years.
But Mr Hare rejected claims that the YMCA had a cultural problem that prevented staff from reporting child safety breaches by Lord Lord.
Staff members gave evidence that they had witnessed such breaches, including Lord being alone with the children, privately guarding them, letting them sit on his lap, telling them he loved them, and letting them play with his mobile phone.
Danielle Ockwell, who was Lord's subordinate and asked for child safety training because she was concerned about his behaviour, testified that Jacqui Barnat, head of children's services at the YMCA in Caringbah, who was Lord's superior, was "very intimidating and often difficult to talk to him about."
The CEO said he doesn't accept staff evidence that they felt comfortable contacting their superiors and reporting the actions.
Instead, he said that their friendship with the Lord clouded their judgment, and that's why they didn't report the problem.
Mr Hare said he had told the YMCA board in New South Wales that the lesson of the "Jonathan Lord case" for the organisation was that the staff had "not reported" and the board agreed with him.
Mr Hare said the decision to have staff sign confidentiality agreements shortly after the allegations emerged was made by YMCA's general manager of children's services Liam Whitley.
He said the aim was to avoid disturbing the evidence, but was "overzealous" and poorly executed.
Child sexual abuse expert Professor Stephen Smallbone, of Griffith University, told the commission that the YMCA in New South Wales was not an organisation safe for children between 2009 and 2011.
He said there were serious problems in recruiting, vetting, incorporating, training and staffing.
The hearing was adjourned until December 20.
