FAA: Air passengers can now use technological achievements on planes (but not make calls from their mobile phones)
Airline passengers will be able to use their electronic devices "gate-to-gate" – in addition to calling from their mobile phones – to read, play games, watch movies, and listen to music under eagerly awaited new rules issued Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA).
However, passengers should not expect changes to occur immediately.
How quickly the change is implemented will vary by airline, FAA Administrator Michael Huerta said at a news conference.
Airlines will need to demonstrate to the FAA how much their aircraft comply with the new rules and that they have updated the cabin crew training manuals and equipment storage guidelines to comply with the new rules.
The FAA said it has already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices on aircraft.
Among the companies that have already submitted plans are Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the status of such a plan, we can improve the widespread use of electronic devices very quickly," the FAA said in a statement.
Currently, passengers are required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the plane doors close.
They can't turn them on until the plane reaches an altitude of 3 kilometers and the captain has issued a warrant.
Passengers are expected to turn off their devices again when the plane descends to land and do not turn them on until the plane is on the ground.
Under the new rules, airlines whose aircraft are properly protected from electronic interference can allow their passengers to use their devices during takeoff, landing and taxiing, the FAA said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft that have been modified to allow passengers to use Wifi at higher altitudes are expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Professional Stewards Association, welcomed the changes.
"Once the new rules are safely implemented -- and we work closely with transport companies on this -- it will be a success," Glading said in a statement.
Frankly, we're tired of looking like "watchmen."
However, internet surfing, emailing and texting or downloading data will continue to be prohibited below 3 kilometers of altitude, the agency said.
Passengers will be notified to switch their smartphones, tablets and other devices to air mode.
So still no Words with friends, an online scrabble game played by actor Alec Baldwin on his smartphone in 2011, when, as is well known, he was thrown off an American Airlines plane because he refused to turn off his device when the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices like laptops will have to continue to be stored because of fears that someone might get hurt if they were flying around the cabin.
Calls from mobile phones will continue to be banned on board.
The rules for using cell phones are determined not by the FAA, but by the U.S. Federal Telecommunications Committee.
The FAA may lift the ban on some electronic devices during takeoff and landing.
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board, a national transportation safety expert, told CBS News that cell phones continue to be considered a risk.
"Mobile phones are a real problem, not only because they can potentially create interference with navigational devices, but we also know from FCC data that they can cause interference to transmission towers in the air," Rosenker said.
A industry advisory committee created by the FAA to investigate the issue proposed last month that the government allow the wider use of electronic devices.
The FAA has been under pressure in recent years to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics, such as Senator Claire McCaskill, Democrat of Missouri, argue that there is no legal security reason for the ban.
Restrictions are also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of such devices is ubiquitous.
Some studies suggest that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore the obligation to turn off their devices.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by passengers in 1966 in response to interference with navigation and communication equipment when passengers began carrying FM radios, a technical prom of the time.
New airlines are much more resentful of electrical systems than previous generations, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA to be resistant to electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers wi-fi at cruising altitudes for several years.
Plans modified for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
Under the new rules, the vast majority of airlines should adapt to greater use of electronic devices, Huert said.
Today's electronic devices generally emit much less intensive radio broadcasting than previous generations.
For example, e-readers emit only minimal broadcasts when you turn a page.
But the broadcast is stronger when devices download or send data.
There is a significant number of people pushing for restrictions on the use of these devices by passengers Amazon.com.
In 2011, representatives of this company loaded the airliner with their Kindle electronic readers and conducted a test flight, but no problem emerged.
Members of the FAA advisory committee expressed mixed feelings about whether these facilities pose any risks.
Douglas Kidd of the National Airline Passengers Association said he believes the interference from these devices is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other committee members have said that there are only fragmented reports from pilots to support the fact that such devices can cause interference with aviation systems, and most of these reports are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order passengers to turn off equipment while flying low-visibility instruments.
The travel industry group welcomed these changes and, in its opinion, this is a sensible course of action for the travelling public, which uses technology extensively.
"We are pleased that the FAA has recognized that a pleasant travel experience is not against safety," said Roger Dow, executive director of the American Travel Association.
