Six out of ten companies are preparing for the new Civil Code
Six out of ten companies are intensively preparing for the impending effectiveness of the new Civil Code and the Commercial Corporations Act from 1 January 2014.
Only eight percent of the firms surveyed said they had not addressed issues related to the two key codes in their company.
This results from a survey by Ambruz & Dark Deloitte Legal, which surveyed the opinions of 108 Czech companies.
As the effective date of both key codes approaches, it is only now at the last minute that many managers are beginning to realise how much influence they can have on their companies' business.
In our opinion, the biggest changes in private law in the last 50 years will affect all citizens and companies in the Czech Republic.
Because of politicians' lagging, the business sector has long been uncertain whether or not revolutionary changes will eventually happen.
"Now, however, they have only a few weeks left to make the transition to the new law without complications for their companies," commented Jan Spáčil, partner of Ambruz & Dark Deloitte Legal.
Of the 61 percent of companies heavily involved in the new laws, 26 percent said their companies had already taken all necessary measures to be ready in time.
Furthermore, 35 percent of companies in this number are preparing to take the necessary measures in the near future.
By contrast, one in five companies has not yet dealt with recodifications, yet they have a concrete idea of how to prepare for them.
A total of 11 percent have no opinion and cannot assess the issue.
Only eight percent of companies admit that they have not yet addressed the issues related to recodifications.
The most important legal issue related to the new Civil Code for the largest number of companies surveyed is the conclusion of new contracts (21 percent), followed by the resolution of terms and conditions (16 percent), as well as changes in the land register and liability for damages (ten percent each).
For contracts, one of the most important innovations of the entire recodification will take place, which is the unification of the treaty arrangements only within the framework of the new Civil Code.
The current parallel regulation in both the Civil and Commercial Code will disappear, as a result of which the contract law should become clearer for citizens and entrepreneurs.
"In the case of entrepreneurs, the new regulation will offer a lot of news with an emphasis on greater freedom of organization of relationships," said Lukáš Poddaný, a lawyer at Ambruz & Dark Deloitte Legal.
In the context of the Corporations Act, almost a quarter of companies consider the issue of increasing the liability of statutory bodies to be the most important issue.
The following are topics related to changes in the convening and course of the general meeting (15 percent) and the representation of the company (14 percent).
The new legislation means tightening up obligations and possible impacts for statutory bodies, especially in situations where a company is in danger of going into decline or falling into it.
"In practice, this means that if the members of the boards and the executives of the companies do not act with the care of a proper manager and avert the impending decline of the company, they may lose the benefit gained for the performance of their duties only in the last two years," added Spáčil.
NSA revelations increase social paranoia of surveillance by the state
One peaceful day in late August, a German police helicopter buzzed over the U.S. Consular Office in Frankfurt, the capital of the German economy.
At the behest of the Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution (BfV), Germany's domestic intelligence agency, the purpose of the mission was to take photographs of the roof of the American forward patrol, which is located less than 5 km from the European Central Bank and the Bundesbank.
German media say the BfV hoped to identify the presence of listening antennas, and the event triggered an exchange of views between the US and German foreign ministers in Berlin.
James Clapper, america's director of national intelligence, insisted again in September that the United States was not using its foreign intelligence capabilities "to steal the trade secrets of foreign companies for the benefit of American companies, the way they strengthen their international competitiveness or increase their profits."
But ever since Edward Snowden, who went from associate to informant, began uncovering his valuable collection from covert surveillance by the United States, European governments and business leaders no longer know whether to believe the director's words.
After reports that the US National Security Agency was spying on a Brazilian oil company and gained access to data available to US cloud providers including Google and Yahoo, the general paranoia about state surveillance has reached new proportions.
The final straw came with the revelation that Chancellor Angela Merkel's phone may have been bugged for a decade.
If the most powerful person in Europe can be targeted, then leading entrepreneurs are certainly potential targets.
Snowden has made the intense cooperation between US intelligence services and companies more transparent.
I would say that it is possible that this data is being used for mutual benefit.
"Germany needs to wake up," said Oliver Grün, president of BITMi, which represents small and medium-sized IT companies in Germany.
According to a survey released in July by the consultancy EY, German companies believe that the US now poses as much risk as China when it comes to industrial espionage and data theft.
But so far, there is no evidence in the entire dossier revealed by Mr Snowden that the United States passed on trade secrets of foreign firms to its own companies.
Politicians expressed concern that the EU lacked certain IT and Internet capabilities and said it should seek to reduce its dependence on the US:
Business leaders are skeptical.
There are voices from the German Parliament that we should make a German Google.
I can just close my eyes and slowly open them again...
That's not the way, says Hasso Plattner, chairman of German software company SAP.
If someone wanted a strong European IT industry, they shouldn't have let them die 20 years ago.
Everything in Germany is subsidized, from coal to cars and farmers.
Everything but the IT industry.
Yet the scale and technical sophistication of the US spy agencies revealed by Snowden is shocking to some companies, who have so far believed that China poses the greatest threat from surveillance.
There is a big turnaround in cloud computing, where European leaders have more broadly recognized that data stored in the US falls under its jurisdiction and is therefore potentially challengeable.
According to a survey conducted by the Cloud Security Alliance, about 10 percent of non-U.S. members canceled plans to use a U.S.-based cloud provider after the unveiling of the U.S. Prism data mining program.
Jim Snabe, one of SAP's CEOs, says: "We have a new question for customers that wasn't here a year ago - where is my data stored and can you guarantee that it will physically remain in this jurisdiction?"
Many German high-powered officials argue that the latest reports are just confirmation of what they already knew: that powerful states want to steal their most valuable secrets, and that data must be protected at all costs.
That economic espionage is being carried out is no surprise.
It's always been happening.
"This has been a fundamental issue for many years, and it hasn't changed significantly during the current discussion," says Kurt Bock, CEO of BASF, an agrochemicals company.
The Americans are spying on us at a commercial and industrial level, just as we are spying on them because it is in our national interest to defend our businesses.
Corporate leaders generally don't want to brag about the countermeasures they've taken to potentially give the attacker an advantage.
In the case of large companies, it has long been recalled that taking a free USB storage disk at the fair or leaving an unprotected laptop in a hotel room is, to say the least, unreasonable.
Ulrich Hackenberg, a board member of Audi, says it has been common practice for many years to collect mobile phones before a board meeting so that they cannot be used as a listening device.
Germany's BfV advises executives to consider using simple prepaid mobile phones on foreign trips because of the risk that smartphones can be embezzed.
Prepaid mobile phones are then thrown away.
However, there is a concern that SMEs will continue to be vulnerable to hacking and surveillance.
In Germany, many of these companies are global market leaders in their specific areas.
"SMEs often lack the experience, staff and financial resources to effectively protect corporate secrets against unauthorised access," the BfV warns in its report.
The US warns its own companies against economic espionage by other countries.
According to the Washington Post, US national intelligence estimate documents in February put France alongside Russia and Israel in the second row of perpetrators involved in hacking for economic intelligence, just behind China.
A board member at a German risk-free society concluded that when it comes to economic espionage, "the French are the worst."
Bernard Squarcini, the former head of France's internal intelligence agency DCRI, said in an interview this month: "The services know perfectly well that all countries, even when cooperating in the fight against terrorism, are spying on their allies."
New nicotine vaccine can take away the pleasures of smoking
Scientists have developed a nicotine vaccine that can take away the pleasure of smoking a cigarette.
A single dose of the vaccine was able to protect the mouse from nicotine addiction for life.
Before human trials, more tests need to be performed that will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical School in New York says the early signs are good.
"We strongly hope that this kind of vaccination strategy can finally help the millions of smokers who have tried to quit and exhausted all the methods available on the market today, but have found that their nicotine addiction is strong enough to overcome all current approaches," Professor Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been designed to carry genetic information to create anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then begin to form a smooth stream of these antibodies.
Antibodies haunt all nicotine molecules in the bloodstream and neutralize them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from getting nicotine hit.
In the tests, vaccinated mice that were additionally supplied with nicotine continued their normal activities.
But mice that were not vaccinated "calmed down," the researchers said, a sign that nicotine had entered their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
Injections had to be given so often as to maintain sufficient levels of antibodies, so they proved expensive and impractical.
The cost of new vaccines should be much lower, since they convert liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if future vaccines are completely safe for humans, they could be given to children before they want to try a cigarette, thus avoiding nicotine addiction.
However, it would be much more likely to be used by smokers to stop.
"They'll know that if they start smoking again, they won't get any benefit from the nicotine vaccine, and that will help them get rid of that habit," he said.
British scientists said the results were interesting, but cautioned that more research was needed.
The Desperate Cry of Obama's Voter
I voted for Obama twice – I shared hope for a possible change
He says Obama's sincere efforts derailed the Republican Party's filibuster
Obstructionary Policy Cannot Excuse the Woes of Obamacare Websites or Drone Strikes
Obama's 2008 campaign memoir is a sad reminder of what may have happened
Nathaniel P. Morris is in his second year of medical school at Harvard.
I read a very sad book these days.
I thought this book would cheer me up during the gloomy days of my second year at medical school and restore a modind of hope in me.
It's called "The Audacity to Win" and it's a reel of Barack Obama's 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish my patient reviews in the evening and go to bed, the book brings me back to a time when politics inspired millions of people and speeches took your breath away.
The election ended in overwhelming dominance, and television news made us reflect on the historical value of this moment.
My classmates wept with joy, and my parents kept the newspaper they could get.
A young team of visionaries headed to the White House, and the nation was ready for change.
During his inauguration in 2008, Obama had 82 percent support.
And this is where I close the book.
Going into the present is a rude awakening, like waking up from a dream.
It's hard to remember these optimistic days – they seem distant memories, sad reminders of missed opportunities.
Indeed, in the years after I threw in my first ballot, there have been changes.
It was definitely nothing I imagined.
I recognize that Obama has achieved a number of great and varied achievements – from the Affordable Care Act to the removal of our troops from Iraq and the end of the "ask no questions, say nothing" policy after the killing of Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I believe that partisan obstruction has reversed so many efforts to move our nation forward: immigration reform, the public's ability to choose health care, and the closure of the Guantanamo base, among other things.
But after many situations where I defended the Obama administration in front of colleagues and friends, I have reached an absolute limit in terms of the explanations they can provide.
I found myself in a place of political despair.
The Republican filibuster cannot explain agreeing to eavesdrop on foreign leaders or drone strikes that kill innocent children overseas.
They cannot explain the fact that the National Security Agency collects data on Americans' private lives, nor that it pursues those who expose government misconduct.
They cannot be held responsible for the execution of Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, without due process, or for cutting public contributions and spending during presidential campaigns.
They cannot justify the findings of a report that says the White House's efforts to silence the media are "the most aggressive ... from the Nixon administration".
And most recently, they can't even excuse the inability to create a simple website more than three years after the Affordable Care Act was signed.
I don't know if that's what to expect.
Whether, at the age of 18, I should have known that government power might conflict with the political campaigns that preceded it.
Elected office is clearly not predictable, and our public conversations will be shaped by an opposition political party and random events like the Newton massacre.
However, all the examples I have given above largely appear to be the result of the administration's own decision.
And that's what bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney was a confused and unassued alternative, and he seemed unable to consolidate his policies or position.
I had a feeling that a second term for Obama, free from the pressure of the next election, would fulfill the hopes we had once heard of.
Yet returning to 2008 – with Obama's support falling below 45% this week – is getting harder with this book.
It makes me remember the many promises that have disappeared.
This week, I read a chapter in my book about how Obama suffered a crushing defeat to Clinton in the Pennsylvania primary.
At an additional meeting during the campaign, he told his staff that he had to get back on pace and stay true to his mission.
"I want our magic back," he said.
We mustn't forget who we are.
Five years have passed, Mr. President, and I completely agree with you.
The ideas expressed in this commentary are exclusively those of Nathaniel Morris.
