Syria has destroyed its means of producing chemical weapons, says supervisory authority
Syria has destroyed vital equipment for the production of chemical weapons and poison gas mummies, the Committee on Global Chemical Weapons Oversight said on Thursday, as fierce conflicts erupted in the north of the country, not far from one of the sites where toxic substances are expected to be stored.
Also on Thursday, a Syrian activist group said that more than 120,000 people have been killed since the civil war began nearly three years ago.
The announcement by the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons came the day before November 1,
the deadline set by this Organisation, based in The Hague, for the destruction or dismantling of all chemical weapons and chemical mixing machinery to create toxic gas and to supply ammunition.
The completion of this essentially initial phase of destruction is an important milestone in an ambitious timetable that aims to destroy all of Damascus' chemical weapons by mid-2014.
The destruction of equipment means that Syria will no longer be able to produce new chemical weapons.
But Damascus has yet to begin the destruction of existing weapons and supplies.
The country is believed to have about 1,000 tons of chemicals and weapons, including mustard gas and sarin nerve gas.
The announcement came as fighting raged in the city of Safira on Thursday, which experts say is the headquarters of a chemical weapons factory and storage, the Britain-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights said.
The activist group, which monitored the total number of victims through a network of activists in Syria, reported on Thursday that 120,296 people had died.
Of these, 61,067 are to be civilians, including 6,365 children.
The ruling party is to have 29,954 members of Bashar al-Assad's armed forces, 18,678 pro-government fighters and 187 militants from Lebanon's Hezbollah.
Among those killed are 2,202 government defectors and some 5,375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
On July 25, the UN estimated that 100,000 people had died in the conflict since March 2011.
This number has not been updated since.
The conflict has forced some 2 million people to leave the country.
Assad's forces have been fighting insurgents in Safira, many of whom are affiliated with Al Qaeda, for weeks.
The Observatory said on Thursday that the losses were on both sides, but did not have specific figures.
The fighting has underscored the danger faced by chemical weapons inspectors, who face tight deadlines in their mission to rid Syria of its chemical arsenal amid syria's ongoing civil war.
A statement from the OPCW, which works closely with the UN, said his team was now "satisfied that it has verified – and monitored the destruction – of Syria's declared essential equipment for production and mixing/filling."
He added that "no further control activities are currently planned."
Earlier this week, inspectors said they had completed the first round of verification work, visiting 21 of the 23 sites declared by Damascus.
Inspectors said they were unable to visit two locations due to security concerns.
On Thursday, the OPCW said that according to Syria, the two sites had been "abandoned and ... the chemical weapons programme items it contained have been moved to two other declared sites that have been checked'.
It was not immediately clear whether the facility in Safira was one of those places that OPCW inspectors could not visit.
Syria has agreed to a plan to completely destroy its chemical weapons, which must be approved next month by the OPCW's executive committee.
"I bow to the courage and bravery you have shown in fulfilling this most demanding mission this organization has ever had," said Observer Director Ahmet Uzumcu in a commentary issued by the OPCW.
Now in its third year, sunni Muslim rebels and assad's government, with their security forces full of members of the Alawite sect, an offshoot of Shiite Islam, are facing each other in the civil war.
As for further developments, the head of the Observatory, Rami Abdul Rahman, said there was a powerful explosion inside an air defense facility in Syria's coastal province of Lázikiya on Wednesday.
He said the cause of the explosion was unknown.
