Early puberty: Mature earlier
Research has shown that African-American women and Hispanic women reach puberty earlier than their white peers.
Physical changes don't mean puberty is coming
It is not proven that hormones or other chemicals are behind this
Experts say that one of the triggers of earlier puberty may be the obesity epidemic.
The trend of early puberty is not so noticeable in boys.
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist who specializes in children's health and family issues.
Should a mother be horrified when her daughter's breasts and pubic hair start growing at 7 or 8 years old?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent a new standard.
"I've spent a lot of time making sure my parents that it's not usually a sign of rapid development toward full puberty," Kaplowitz said.
Visible signs of development, such as breast growth, pubic hair and armpits, and body odo, appear earlier in girls.
In the last forty years, however, there has been little shift in the age at which the first menstruation occurs.
In the United States, the average age is now 12.5 years, compared to 12.75 in 1970.
"When breasts start to develop, it's at least two to three years before the first menstruation occurs," said Kaplowitz, who is also the author of "Early Puberty in Girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem."
The most reliable test of how puberty will continue is time.
It is discussed what activates the actual beginning of puberty, but if breast growth is accompanied by a growth spurt before the age of 8, the girl is considered "precocious".
In most cases, the process slows down or stops – which can be closely monitored by children's doctors.
Faster growth may be a reason for the endocrinologist to perform tests to eliminate serious problems such as a tumor or cyst.
There are treatments that delay early menstruation and prevent other consequences: premature bone aging, which can eventually lead to a halt in growth and stunting in adulthood.
Recommendations on medications and hormonal treatment depend on the child's age, speed of development, growth rate and emotional maturity.
Psychosociological aspects are also important.
When it comes to the use of drugs, Kaplowitz is cautious, but acknowledges that "suppressing puberty can alleviate problems with a girl's behavior and her feelings that she differs from her peers."
Understandable is another big problem: Parents simply don't want their very young daughters to have menstruation.
"They're worried that she might get pregnant or manage hygiene," Kaplowitz said.
"It was a shock," recalls one woman whose daughter began her period at the age of 10.
Although there were hints and we talked about menstruation, she wasn't prepared emotionally.
She came home from school scared and angry that she was the first of her friends.
There are many well-known theories about the causes of premature puberty.
However, there is not yet a continuous body of evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, environmental chemicals or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
Boys – like girls – reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz advocates the assumption that the obesity epidemic is the most serious reason.
In 2001, he helped conduct a study in girls aged 6 to 9 years that linked body fat to the timing of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American women and Hispanic women tend to reach puberty before their white counterparts.
Explanations vary.
From a global perspective, early puberty patterns seem to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climates to genes.
Another puzzle: Although boys already experience facial hair and pubic hair at a young age, the trend towards the full flowering of early puberty is not as pronounced as that of girls.
Other doctors attending the American Association of PediatricIans (AAP) conference added more complexity to the topic.
Acne and pubic hair are common even in infants and toddlers.
"We have to be careful about how we identify the actual onset of puberty," said Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to get instructions from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
"It may mean having to talk to the child sooner than you'd expect," Kaplowitz advised.
If you stay calm, your child will probably react well.
Girls who develop earlier need reassurance that even if it happens prematurely, this process is a normal part of life.
